SIMPLE: grind
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grind
<hw>Grind</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Ground</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Grinding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>grindan</ets>; perh.
akin to L. <ets>frendere</ets> to gnash, grind. Cf.
<er>Grist</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reduce to powder by friction,
as in a mill, or with the teeth; to crush into small fragments; to
produce as by the action of millstones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take the millstones, and <qex>grind</qex> meal.</q> <rj><qau>Is.
xivii. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wear down, polish, or sharpen, by friction; to
make smooth, sharp, or pointed; to whet, as a knife or drill; to rub
against one another, as teeth, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To oppress by severe exactions; to harass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>grind</qex> the subject or defraud the prince.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To study hard for examination; -- commonly used with
<ptcl>away</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>grind away at</ex> one's
studies</as>.</def> <mark>[College Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grind</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grind
<hw>Grind</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
perform the operation of grinding something; to turn the
millstones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Send thee⟦br⟧
Into the common prison, there to <qex>grind</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become ground or pulverized by friction; <as>as,
this corn <ex>grinds</ex> well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To become polished or sharpened by friction; <as>as,
glass <ex>grinds</ex> smooth; steel <ex>grinds</ex> to a sharp
edge.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To move with much difficulty or friction; to
grate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To perform hard and distasteful service; to drudge;
to study hard, as for an examination.</def> <au>Farrar.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grind</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grind
<hw>Grind</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of reducing to
powder, or of sharpening, by friction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any severe continuous work or occupation; esp., hard
and uninteresting study.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>T.
Hughes.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A student that studies hard; a dig; a wonk.</def>
<mark>[College Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grinded</ent>⟦br⟧
